/* 1847 to 1901 */ Westinghouse's enthusiasm for AC power can be traced squarely to Europe. AC power has the advantage of being easily "step-uppable" and "step-downable" via transformers, so current can be swapped for voltage at will. This advantageously leverages the fundamental physical reality that energy loss through a conductor increases with current squared, so high voltages are used for long-distance power transmission, thus saving energy while also shrinking the diameters of conductors.
